WEBVTT

00:02.502 --> 00:04.437
[***]

00:05.472 --> 00:07.507
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

00:07.540 --> 00:09.642
NARRATOR:
<i>I got a new bike when we moved.</i>

00:09.676 --> 00:13.179
<i>Now, before 13-year-olds</i>
<i>started driving Bentleys,</i>

00:13.213 --> 00:15.382
<i>a new bike</i>
<i>was pretty impressive.</i>

00:15.415 --> 00:17.317
<i>My last bike had gotten stolen,</i>

00:17.350 --> 00:19.319
<i>so my father had one rule.</i>

00:19.352 --> 00:21.154
Don't let nobody ride it.

00:21.187 --> 00:23.289
NARRATOR:
<i>My mother had one rule too.</i>

00:23.323 --> 00:25.325
Chris, you can only ride

00:25.358 --> 00:27.861
from this end of the block
to that end of the block.

00:27.894 --> 00:31.698
NARRATOR:
<i>Sometimes, I could only ride in</i>
<i>a circle in front of the house.</i>

00:31.731 --> 00:34.300
<i>There were hundreds of kids</i>
<i>on my block,</i>

00:34.334 --> 00:36.302
<i>but only four fathers.</i>

00:36.336 --> 00:37.804
<i>There was Mr. Jenkins.</i>

00:37.837 --> 00:40.740
<i>He had all girls,</i>
<i>so he was always screaming.</i>

00:40.774 --> 00:42.108
Hey! Hey!

00:42.142 --> 00:43.777
You boys get away
from my daughter.

00:43.810 --> 00:46.212
NARRATOR:
<i>Mr. Parrish's wife</i>
<i>cheated on him,</i>

00:46.246 --> 00:47.580
<i>so he was always checking</i>

00:47.614 --> 00:49.549
<i>to see if his kids</i>
<i>looked like him.</i>

00:49.582 --> 00:53.853
<i>He was the first man</i>
<i>in Bed-Stuy to get a DNA test.</i>

00:53.887 --> 00:57.524
<i>Mr. Hutchins had two grown sons</i>
<i>who wouldn't move out.</i>

00:57.557 --> 01:00.593
<i>They're holding out like, "Last</i>
<i>one dies gets the apartment."</i>

01:00.627 --> 01:03.596
<i>And there's my dad, Julius.</i>
MAN: Morning, Julius!

01:03.630 --> 01:05.832
NARRATOR:
<i>Because unemployment</i>
<i>was so high,</i>

01:05.865 --> 01:07.734
<i>the dads all knew each other,</i>

01:07.767 --> 01:09.602
<i>'cause they were the only men</i>
<i>going to work in the morning.</i>

01:09.636 --> 01:12.339
<i>Between these four dads,</i>
<i>they had 16 jobs</i>

01:12.372 --> 01:14.874
<i>and worked 492 hours a week!</i>

01:14.908 --> 01:17.610
<i>Bed-Stuy wasn't the best</i>
<i>neighborhood in Brooklyn,</i>

01:17.644 --> 01:19.746
<i>but it wasn't quite as bad</i>
<i>as people thought.</i>

01:19.779 --> 01:23.383
<i>You say, "Bed-Stuy,"</i>
<i>and people think this:</i>

01:23.416 --> 01:25.752
[PEOPLE CLAMORING]

01:25.785 --> 01:28.121
[SIREN WAILING]

01:32.192 --> 01:34.394
NARRATOR:
<i>But it was</i>
<i>a pretty regular place.</i>

01:34.427 --> 01:36.262
<i>Mail got delivered.</i>

01:36.296 --> 01:37.564
<i>People ran businesses.</i>

01:37.597 --> 01:39.733
<i>Kids played in the street.</i>

01:39.766 --> 01:41.868
<i>My problem was,</i>
<i>since I didn't go to school</i>

01:41.901 --> 01:44.471
<i>in the neighborhood,</i>
<i>the thugs didn't know me,</i>

01:44.504 --> 01:47.674
<i>so they would rob me</i>
<i>almost every single day.</i>

01:47.707 --> 01:49.275
Yo, yo, yo, little man.

01:50.910 --> 01:52.178
You live around here?

01:52.212 --> 01:53.646
I live right down there.

01:53.680 --> 01:55.648
NARRATOR:
<i>I could tell him where I lived,</i>

01:55.682 --> 01:57.517
<i>but then he might</i>
<i>break in my house.</i>

01:57.550 --> 01:58.918
Man, what school you go to?

01:58.952 --> 02:00.286
Corleone Junior High.

02:00.320 --> 02:01.421
Corleone?

02:01.454 --> 02:03.390
You ever heard of that?
No.

02:03.423 --> 02:05.525
Y'all ever heard
of Corleone Junior High?

02:05.558 --> 02:07.193
NARRATOR:
<i>These fools</i>
<i>never heard of Yale!</i>

02:07.227 --> 02:08.895
Hey, man, we ain't never
heard of that.

02:08.928 --> 02:11.731
So, uh...why don't you
let me hold a dollar?

02:11.765 --> 02:14.534
NARRATOR:
<i>In case you didn't know,</i>
<i>when a criminal says,</i>

02:14.567 --> 02:16.269
<i>"Let me hold something,"</i>

02:16.302 --> 02:17.937
<i>that means you're never</i>
<i>getting it back.</i>

02:17.971 --> 02:20.173
Let me hold
your cash register.

02:21.007 --> 02:22.509
Thank you.

02:22.542 --> 02:24.377
NARRATOR:
<i>It could have been worse.</i>

02:24.411 --> 02:26.680
<i>I could have been going</i>
<i>to pay the light bill.</i>

02:26.713 --> 02:28.682
[***]

02:34.587 --> 02:37.724
<i>* Aw, make it funky now </i>

03:00.780 --> 03:03.416
NARRATOR:
<i>Nothing could stop</i>
<i>my father from working</i>

03:03.450 --> 03:05.719
<i>unless work stopped working.</i>

03:05.752 --> 03:08.722
<i>Local truckers are on strike</i>
<i>today over dangerous conditions</i>

03:08.755 --> 03:11.691
<i>brought about by what they call</i>
<i>"lack of adequate signage."</i>

03:11.725 --> 03:13.993
<i>Apparently, a driver</i>
<i>was injured in an explosion</i>

03:14.027 --> 03:17.831
<i>caused when gasoline fumes were</i>
<i>ignited as he filled his tank.</i>

03:17.864 --> 03:21.334
I can't believe this!
What's wrong?

03:21.368 --> 03:23.803
I'm on strike.
What happened?

03:23.837 --> 03:25.739
They say we're
in dangerous conditions,

03:25.772 --> 03:28.308
and they got to put
warning signs on the truck,

03:28.341 --> 03:29.976
'cause some guy
got in an accident.

03:30.010 --> 03:32.612
NARRATOR:
<i>It was a little more</i>
<i>than an accident.</i>

03:36.783 --> 03:39.586
Well, how long do you think
this is gonna last?

03:39.619 --> 03:42.655
I don't know, but I can't
be out of work right now.

03:42.689 --> 03:46.326
I'm trying to put some extra
money down on the heat bill.

03:46.359 --> 03:48.728
Plus, the kids need
new winter coats.

03:48.762 --> 03:50.830
Well, Chris could wear
Drew's old coat.

03:50.864 --> 03:52.465
And Tanya will be okay.

03:52.499 --> 03:54.968
Her sleeves might be
a little short, but we'll just

03:55.001 --> 03:57.037
buy her longer gloves.

03:57.070 --> 04:00.306
Fool don't know better
than to light fire around gas,

04:00.340 --> 04:01.508
and now I'm all messed up.

04:01.541 --> 04:03.677
Baby, don't worry,
I can just go down

04:03.710 --> 04:06.446
to the temp agency on Monday
and get a job.

04:06.479 --> 04:07.781
They like me.

04:09.916 --> 04:13.486
NARRATOR:
<i>My mother was pretty good with</i>
<i>people when she wanted to be,</i>

04:13.520 --> 04:16.356
<i>so she never had any problem</i>
<i>getting a job.</i>

04:16.389 --> 04:17.624
Oh, you can stick it!

04:17.657 --> 04:19.759
I told you not
to call my old job.

04:22.495 --> 04:25.498
You trying to get
that secretary job?

04:25.532 --> 04:27.734
Girl,
I like your shoes.

04:27.767 --> 04:28.802
Rochelle.

04:33.073 --> 04:35.375
Hi. Nice to meet you.

04:35.408 --> 04:37.544
[***]

04:40.680 --> 04:43.383
Whoa, whoa!
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

04:43.416 --> 04:45.051
Yo, little man,
let me hold a dollar.

04:45.085 --> 04:46.419
I don't have any money.

04:46.453 --> 04:47.921
So, what you got, then?
Nothing!

04:47.954 --> 04:51.057
I stopped carrying stuff, 'cause
every time I come by here,

04:51.091 --> 04:52.759
you ask me where I live.

04:52.792 --> 04:55.495
I say, "Right down there,"
and then you rob me anyway.

04:55.528 --> 04:58.064
You live around here?
Yeah, right down there.

04:58.098 --> 04:59.799
That's a nice bike.

04:59.833 --> 05:00.934
Look at that. Yeah.

05:00.967 --> 05:02.635
That's new?
Yeah.

05:02.669 --> 05:05.105
Why don't you, uh,
let me take a ride on your bike.

05:05.138 --> 05:07.807
NARRATOR:
<i>Translation:</i>
<i>Can I steal your bike, please?</i>

05:07.841 --> 05:09.743
My dad said not
to let anybody ride it.

05:09.776 --> 05:11.745
BOY:
Why don't you guys
leave him alone?

05:11.778 --> 05:14.614
Yo, Fat Mike.
You know this dude?

05:14.647 --> 05:16.549
Yeah. He lives
right up the street.

05:16.583 --> 05:18.551
Man, why you ain't say
you know Fat Mike?

05:18.585 --> 05:20.387
NARRATOR:
<i>Uh, because I don't.</i>

05:20.420 --> 05:22.856
Fat Mike...
you know him?

05:25.191 --> 05:27.560
No. Come on, man.

05:32.165 --> 05:33.566
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

05:33.600 --> 05:35.568
Let me hold a dollar.

05:35.602 --> 05:37.437
Why do you hang out
with those guys?

05:37.470 --> 05:39.172
I just know them
from the block.

05:39.205 --> 05:41.975
NARRATOR:
<i>I wasn't sure why Fat Mike</i>
<i>was hanging with me,</i>

05:42.008 --> 05:45.178
<i>but as long as it kept me from</i>
<i>getting robbed, I was cool.</i>

05:45.211 --> 05:46.680
You go to school around here?

05:46.713 --> 05:48.515
Yeah. Where do you go?

05:48.548 --> 05:51.017
Corleone. It's all the way
over in Brooklyn Beach.

05:51.051 --> 05:52.452
Why do you go
over there?

05:52.485 --> 05:55.855
My mom.
She thinks it's better.

05:55.889 --> 05:57.857
That's a nice bike.

05:57.891 --> 05:58.992
How long you had it?

05:59.025 --> 06:01.027
About three months now.

06:01.061 --> 06:02.495
I got it for my birthday.

06:02.529 --> 06:03.963
I wish I had that one.

06:05.632 --> 06:07.133
Why do they call you Fat Mike?

06:07.167 --> 06:09.069
They just always did.

06:09.102 --> 06:11.838
NARRATOR:
<i>There were about ten Mikes</i>
<i>in my neighborhood.</i>

06:11.871 --> 06:14.708
<i>Big Head Mike spent more time</i>
<i>in jail than out of jail.</i>

06:14.741 --> 06:17.510
<i>White Mike was just a white guy</i>
<i>who lived on the block.</i>

06:17.544 --> 06:19.512
<i>Family didn't have</i>
<i>enough money to leave.</i>

06:19.546 --> 06:21.214
<i>Tall Mike played ball.</i>

06:21.247 --> 06:23.750
<i>Monster Mike just scared kids.</i>

06:23.783 --> 06:25.552
<i>And Mike Mike was actually</i>

06:25.585 --> 06:27.487
<i>the first Mike</i>
<i>that lived on the block.</i>

06:27.520 --> 06:29.889
<i>But his real name was Paul.</i>

06:29.923 --> 06:32.592
FAT MIKE:
Oh, don't be
scared of them.

06:32.625 --> 06:34.828
They'll leave you alone
after a while.

06:34.861 --> 06:37.063
NARRATOR:
<i>Translation:</i>
<i>When they go to jail.</i>

06:37.097 --> 06:38.798
You want to hang out
after school tomorrow?

06:38.832 --> 06:42.202
I can't. I got to go to Jersey
to see my father.

06:42.235 --> 06:45.038
NARRATOR:
<i>I think I was the first kid</i>
<i>that Fat Mike knew</i>

06:45.071 --> 06:47.540
<i>that actually had a father</i>
<i>that lived at home.</i>

06:47.574 --> 06:49.876
All right,
then I'll catch you later.

06:49.909 --> 06:51.845
[***]

06:54.748 --> 06:57.984
NARRATOR:
<i>My father felt uncomfortable</i>
<i>when he didn't have a job.</i>

06:58.018 --> 07:01.521
<i>So when he was home, he would</i>
<i>do any work he could find.</i>

07:01.554 --> 07:03.023
[***]

07:29.115 --> 07:31.017
Five cent worth of bread.

07:33.586 --> 07:35.255
Ten cent worth of Kool-Aid.

07:44.264 --> 07:46.533
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

07:49.602 --> 07:50.804
Hey, man.

07:50.837 --> 07:53.573
You want to take a ride
down to the park?

07:53.606 --> 07:54.974
I can't go
off the block.

07:55.008 --> 07:57.644
[SIGHS]
Well, can I take a ride
on your bike?

07:57.677 --> 07:59.579
Can't let anybody ride it.

07:59.612 --> 08:00.914
I'm only going to the corner.

08:00.947 --> 08:02.982
NARRATOR:
<i>Cool guys always have a way</i>

08:03.016 --> 08:05.552
<i>of making you feel like a punk</i>
<i>if you don't do what they say.</i>

08:05.585 --> 08:06.886
All right, I guess so.

08:09.989 --> 08:12.025
But it's only
down to the corner.

08:12.058 --> 08:14.594
Yeah. Yeah, yeah.

08:15.795 --> 08:17.897
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

08:24.904 --> 08:26.773
Fat Mike!

08:27.907 --> 08:29.309
Fat Mike!

08:31.177 --> 08:33.980
Boy, stop all the hollering
and put your bike up.

08:34.014 --> 08:36.549
It's time to come in.

08:40.253 --> 08:41.621
[***]

08:41.654 --> 08:42.655
Hi, Mom.

08:42.689 --> 08:43.890
TONYA:
Hey, Mom.

08:43.923 --> 08:46.226
Daddy showed me
how to fold napkins.

08:46.259 --> 08:47.894
Julius,
what's all this?

08:47.927 --> 08:50.930
Hey, babe,
how are you doing?

08:50.964 --> 08:54.634
You were working, so I wanted
to have dinner ready for you.

08:54.668 --> 08:56.036
I cleaned the house too.

08:56.069 --> 08:59.005
Daddy washed and ironed
all my school clothes.

08:59.039 --> 08:59.873
Mine too.

08:59.906 --> 09:03.009
He even sewed up
the holes in my socks.

09:03.043 --> 09:04.644
Did he, now?

09:04.678 --> 09:07.647
[CHUCKLES]
Looks like you were
really busy today.

09:07.681 --> 09:09.616
NARRATOR:
<i>You would think my mother</i>
<i>would be happy</i>

09:09.649 --> 09:11.184
<i>that my father</i>
<i>was helping out.</i>

09:11.217 --> 09:15.288
<i>But if losing his job was bad,</i>
<i>doing her job was worse.</i>

09:15.321 --> 09:17.257
You want to eat?

09:17.290 --> 09:19.993
No, I'm not that hungry.

09:22.696 --> 09:24.064
Hey, Mom.

09:24.864 --> 09:26.900
What's wrong with Mom?

09:26.933 --> 09:29.703
She probably got a headache
from work or something.

09:29.736 --> 09:31.204
Uh, did you bring
your bike in?

09:31.237 --> 09:32.672
Yeah.

09:32.706 --> 09:34.708
You didn't let anybody
ride it...
No!

09:34.741 --> 09:37.310
Good. These guys around here
will steal it.

09:37.344 --> 09:42.882
<i>* Everybody Hates Chris </i>

09:51.358 --> 09:53.393
Got that sausage.
I'm full, Dad.

09:53.426 --> 09:55.362
Me too.
Those biscuits were good.

09:55.395 --> 09:56.796
Made 'em from scratch.

09:56.830 --> 09:59.332
Hey, Dad, can we have
bacon tomorrow?

09:59.366 --> 10:01.134
Anything for you, baby.

10:01.167 --> 10:02.268
All right, you guys, uh,

10:02.302 --> 10:03.870
finish getting ready
for school.

10:03.903 --> 10:05.238
All right.
Chris,

10:05.271 --> 10:06.673
I was in
the basement.

10:06.706 --> 10:08.074
I didn't see your bike.

10:08.108 --> 10:10.677
I put it under a sheet
so it wouldn't get dirty.

10:10.710 --> 10:12.212
Not my good sheets?
No, ma'am.

10:12.245 --> 10:14.781
NARRATOR:
<i>If my parents found out</i>
<i>about my bike,</i>

10:14.814 --> 10:16.349
<i>this was gonna be my last meal.</i>

10:16.383 --> 10:17.884
What you put in these eggs?

10:17.917 --> 10:20.353
Just a little ham,
cheddar cheese, season salt,

10:20.387 --> 10:25.225
a touch of basil, and just
a-a little dash of hot sauce.

10:25.258 --> 10:27.127
Taste a little funny.

10:28.895 --> 10:30.230
You want something else?

10:30.263 --> 10:32.365
I'll have some sausage.

10:32.399 --> 10:34.034
Okay.

10:35.268 --> 10:36.803
Mmm.

10:39.406 --> 10:41.875
A little dry.
Rochelle,

10:41.908 --> 10:44.277
I feel bad enough
about not working.

10:44.310 --> 10:45.845
I don't need you around here

10:45.879 --> 10:47.247
complaining about
how I do things.

10:47.280 --> 10:50.216
If you did things right,
I wouldn't have to complain.

10:50.250 --> 10:54.187
Half the stuff around here
I do better than you.

10:54.220 --> 10:56.222
It ain't that hard.

10:56.256 --> 10:58.391
NARRATOR:
<i>My father was the oldest</i>
<i>of 10 brothers and sisters.</i>

10:58.425 --> 11:01.761
<i>He had been cooking</i>
<i>and cleaning all of his life.</i>

11:01.795 --> 11:03.463
<i>But even if the job wasn't</i>
<i>that hard,</i>

11:03.496 --> 11:06.433
<i>he's not supposed to say it.</i>

11:06.466 --> 11:07.867
What?

11:07.901 --> 11:09.269
You got something to say?

11:09.302 --> 11:11.237
[***]

11:14.007 --> 11:16.109
[MAN READS ON-SCREEN TEXT]

11:20.046 --> 11:22.949
Well, ain't this about a b--

11:22.982 --> 11:24.384
[GLASS SHATTERS]
JULIUS: Ooh!

11:24.417 --> 11:25.752
ROCHELLE:
Are you crazy?

11:25.785 --> 11:27.754
You do my job for one day.

11:27.787 --> 11:29.122
[GLASS SHATTERS]
JULIUS: Oh!

11:29.155 --> 11:30.957
ROCHELLE:
And I make that damn hard!

11:30.990 --> 11:33.193
You baking, frying,
biscuit-baking,

11:33.226 --> 11:36.363
pancake-making,
bald-headed bastard!

11:36.396 --> 11:37.831
[GLASS SHATTERS]
JULIUS: Ow!

11:37.864 --> 11:39.833
[CLOCK TICKING]

11:39.866 --> 11:41.801
ROCHELLE:
You must think I'm crazy!

11:41.835 --> 11:43.903
[OBJECTS CRASHING]
[CROWD GASPS]

11:43.937 --> 11:46.973
ROCHELLE:
You can kiss
my ain't-that-hard...

11:47.007 --> 11:48.875
[OBJECTS CRASH]
[CROWD GASPS]

11:48.908 --> 11:51.911
Have you lost your mind?

11:53.580 --> 11:57.384
NARRATOR:
<i>And that was my mother's way</i>
<i>of letting him off easy.</i>

11:57.417 --> 11:58.785
Got that?

11:58.818 --> 12:00.553
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

12:00.587 --> 12:02.188
[LAUGHING]

12:02.222 --> 12:04.290
Oh, yeah.
Hey.

12:04.324 --> 12:05.892
What's up, little man?

12:05.925 --> 12:08.128
I was looking for Fat Mike.
You know Fat Mike?

12:08.161 --> 12:11.197
Yeah. I was here the other day
when y'all tried to rob me.

12:11.231 --> 12:12.298
Oh.

12:12.332 --> 12:15.135
You're the little dude
from across the street, huh?

12:15.168 --> 12:17.303
That's the little dude
from across the street.

12:17.337 --> 12:19.572
Oh, yeah. We didn't know
that was you.

12:19.606 --> 12:22.509
NARRATOR:
<i>You said that</i>
<i>like I had on a disguise.</i>

12:22.542 --> 12:24.344
Man, I ain't seen Fat Mike.

12:24.377 --> 12:25.812
I ain't seen him,
either.

12:25.845 --> 12:27.080
If you see him,
can you let him know

12:27.113 --> 12:28.481
Chris was looking for him?

12:28.515 --> 12:31.284
Yeah.
Little dude?

12:32.419 --> 12:33.520
You know him?

12:35.455 --> 12:36.489
Nope.

12:36.523 --> 12:37.957
All right.
All right.

12:37.991 --> 12:40.293
Yeah, fresh meat.
Yeah, what's up?

12:40.326 --> 12:41.861
Yeah.
Back.

12:41.895 --> 12:43.363
Let me hold a dollar.

12:43.396 --> 12:45.331
[***]

12:49.235 --> 12:51.504
NARRATOR:
<i>I didn't know</i>
<i>Fat Mike's real name.</i>

12:51.538 --> 12:53.139
<i>I didn't know where he lived.</i>

12:53.173 --> 12:55.508
<i>All I knew was,</i>
<i>I had to get my bike back,</i>

12:55.542 --> 12:57.177
<i>because if I didn't...</i>

12:57.210 --> 12:58.378
Mama, where's Chris?

12:58.411 --> 12:59.979
Somebody stole his bike

13:00.013 --> 13:03.016
after I told him not to let
anybody ride it.

13:03.049 --> 13:04.851
So I smacked him
into next week.

13:04.884 --> 13:06.353
I told you.

13:06.386 --> 13:08.555
He'll be back on Tuesday.

13:09.622 --> 13:11.191
[SIGHS]

13:18.331 --> 13:19.632
Chris.
Oh, thanks.

13:19.666 --> 13:21.568
Mom, Dad found $20
cleaning under my bed.

13:21.601 --> 13:23.103
That's nice.

13:23.136 --> 13:24.504
DREW:
He let me keep five.

13:24.537 --> 13:27.107
Daddy, can you fix
my doll's dress? It ripped.

13:27.140 --> 13:28.875
I can do that for you, baby.

13:28.908 --> 13:30.577
Oh, I want Dad to do it.

13:30.610 --> 13:32.178
He sews good.

13:32.212 --> 13:35.281
"Well." I sew well.
I guess you do.

13:35.315 --> 13:37.517
Dad, this is good.
What's this called?

13:37.550 --> 13:39.953
It's nothing. Just...

13:39.986 --> 13:41.888
Mmm, it tastes like syrup.

13:41.921 --> 13:43.957
It's maple barbecue
baked chicken.

13:45.125 --> 13:47.160
Is that why
it's so sweet?

13:47.193 --> 13:50.497
TONYA:
Oh, Ma, Dad cleaned
the dishes good.

13:50.530 --> 13:53.099
I can see myself
in the spoon.

13:53.133 --> 13:55.635
Oh, Dad,
do we have dessert?

13:55.669 --> 13:57.203
Well, do we?

13:58.438 --> 14:00.674
Yeah. Peach cobbler.

14:00.707 --> 14:02.575
Peach cobbler!
CHRIS: Peach cobbler!

14:02.609 --> 14:04.978
Oh, I love peach cobbler! Whoo!

14:05.011 --> 14:07.280
Ma, how come you never
made peach cobbler?

14:07.313 --> 14:10.016
Ma, he made the ice cream
from scratch too.

14:10.050 --> 14:11.418
DREW:
Mm-hmm.

14:11.451 --> 14:12.986
TONYA:
Can you pass
some butter, please?

14:13.019 --> 14:14.487
CHRIS:
It's supposed
to be biscuits.

14:14.521 --> 14:16.089
Yeah. You want
that biscuit?

14:16.122 --> 14:18.024
DREW:
Dad, did you make
the soda too?

14:18.058 --> 14:20.160
[***]

14:25.398 --> 14:27.434
Hey, need any help
with the dishes?

14:27.467 --> 14:29.002
Oh, no, baby, I got it.

14:29.035 --> 14:31.071
Don't worry about it.

14:31.104 --> 14:33.440
Yeah, well, I guess
I'm gonna go to bed, then.

14:33.473 --> 14:34.974
All right.

14:36.176 --> 14:38.211
When do you think
this strike is gonna end?

14:38.244 --> 14:40.947
I don't know. They're still
trying to figure out

14:40.980 --> 14:44.084
who's gonna pay
for the truck signs.

14:44.117 --> 14:46.419
Well, I hope
they figure it out soon.

14:46.453 --> 14:50.290
<i>* ...not the one</i>
<i>She want to spend her life *</i>

14:50.323 --> 14:54.361
<i>* Heart, heartbreak blues </i>

14:54.394 --> 14:57.497
<i>* I never thought</i>
<i>I'd lose the love... *</i>

14:57.530 --> 15:01.267
NARRATOR:
<i>Only a woman can make you</i>
<i>feel wrong for doing right.</i>

15:01.301 --> 15:03.970
JULIUS:
Listen, I need
a favor from you guys.

15:04.004 --> 15:05.038
Okay.
Okay.

15:05.071 --> 15:07.173
Now, this is a little unusual,

15:07.207 --> 15:09.275
but I need you to do
what I tell you.

15:12.145 --> 15:14.047
I want you to mess
the house up.

15:14.080 --> 15:15.482
[GASPS] Whoa.
What?

15:15.515 --> 15:16.750
Mess the house up?

15:16.783 --> 15:18.084
Won't Mama get mad?

15:18.118 --> 15:19.686
Yeah, but don't
worry about it.

15:19.719 --> 15:21.254
Can I set Chris on fire?

15:21.287 --> 15:24.090
No, baby, don't
set Chris on fire, okay?

15:24.124 --> 15:26.993
NARRATOR:
<i>At least this time</i>
<i>she asked for permission.</i>

15:27.027 --> 15:28.061
Okay.

15:28.094 --> 15:29.996
Good. Now mess up
your beds,

15:30.030 --> 15:31.598
eat a snack,
leave your plates out.

15:31.631 --> 15:33.233
Leave your drawers
in the hallway.

15:33.266 --> 15:35.669
Just don't set
your brother on fire, all right?

15:35.702 --> 15:37.270
Now, go!
Yes!

15:37.303 --> 15:39.406
All right, when I get done,
can I go outside?

15:39.439 --> 15:43.009
Yeah, but just out front.
Yeah!

15:43.043 --> 15:44.444
<i>* Yeah </i>

15:44.477 --> 15:46.479
<i>* Get down to work </i>
<i>* Do it </i>

15:46.513 --> 15:48.682
<i>* Yeah </i>
<i>* Do it right </i>

15:48.715 --> 15:50.150
<i>* Yeah, yeah, yeah </i>

15:50.183 --> 15:51.284
<i>* Do it </i>
<i>* Yeah </i>

15:51.317 --> 15:53.620
<i>* Let's get to work </i>

15:53.653 --> 15:58.091
<i>* Do it </i>
<i>* Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah </i>

15:58.124 --> 16:00.326
<i>* Do it</i>
<i>Do it right *</i>

16:02.062 --> 16:04.230
<i>* Do it</i>
<i>Do it right *</i>

16:04.264 --> 16:06.366
<i>* Yeah, yeah, yeah... </i>

16:06.399 --> 16:08.201
NARRATOR:
<i>Black people didn't go</i>
<i>this crazy again</i>

16:08.234 --> 16:10.403
<i>until the L.A. riots.</i>

16:10.437 --> 16:12.772
<i>* Yeah, yeah, yeah</i>
<i>Come on now *</i>

16:12.806 --> 16:15.041
NARRATOR:
<i>I looked everywhere</i>
<i>for Fat Mike.</i>

16:15.075 --> 16:17.444
<i>Well, considering I couldn't</i>
<i>go past the corner,</i>

16:17.477 --> 16:19.446
<i>everywhere was about a block.</i>

16:19.479 --> 16:21.114
Hey, baby.
It's getting late,

16:21.147 --> 16:22.582
so why don't you get
your bike

16:22.615 --> 16:24.184
and come inside
for dinner.

16:24.217 --> 16:28.154
I'm sure your father made
some fantastic meal.

16:28.188 --> 16:30.090
NARRATOR:
<i>I figured maybe if I told her</i>

16:30.123 --> 16:32.359
<i>about my bike outside,</i>
<i> she wouldn't kill me</i>

16:32.392 --> 16:34.494
<i>because of all the witnesses.</i>

16:34.527 --> 16:36.429
Mom, Mom, Mom.

16:38.765 --> 16:40.166
I got to tell
you something.

16:40.200 --> 16:41.534
What is it?

16:41.568 --> 16:43.503
[***]

16:46.573 --> 16:48.108
I love your cooking.

16:48.141 --> 16:49.642
[CHUCKLES]

16:49.676 --> 16:51.344
Thank you, baby.

16:51.378 --> 16:53.279
Get your bike
and come on inside.

16:57.217 --> 16:58.585
Where were you?

16:58.618 --> 17:01.321
You said you'd bring
my bike back two days ago.

17:01.354 --> 17:02.389
Sorry.

17:03.723 --> 17:05.525
That's it? Sorry?

17:05.558 --> 17:08.261
Well, what do you want me
to say? I brought it back.

17:08.294 --> 17:10.797
You act like I was going
to steal it or something.

17:10.830 --> 17:12.499
I did think
you stole it.

17:12.532 --> 17:14.167
Well, I didn't.

17:14.200 --> 17:16.403
NARRATOR:
<i>I didn't know</i>
<i>a lot about Fat Mike,</i>

17:16.436 --> 17:18.738
<i>but that's when I found out</i>
<i>he wasn't a thief.</i>

17:18.772 --> 17:21.074
Hey...
What?

17:22.142 --> 17:23.576
I just didn't know
where you were.

17:23.610 --> 17:27.213
Well, your mom said not to let
anyone ride your bike.

17:27.247 --> 17:29.215
So I kept it so
you wouldn't get in trouble.

17:29.249 --> 17:31.851
NARRATOR:
<i>Now to him, that just makes</i>
<i>perfect sense.</i>

17:31.885 --> 17:33.486
You had my bike,

17:33.520 --> 17:35.855
so why would I want
your bike?

17:35.889 --> 17:37.223
Anyway...

17:37.257 --> 17:38.491
you coming out tomorrow?

17:38.525 --> 17:41.728
Yeah, I guess so.
I'll see you then.

17:41.761 --> 17:44.197
NARRATOR:
<i>That's what they call</i>
<i>a friendship in Bed-Stuy:</i>

17:44.230 --> 17:46.566
<i>a guy who doesn't steal</i>
<i>your bike.</i>

17:47.767 --> 17:49.869
Hey, Ma.
Hi, ba...by.

17:49.903 --> 17:53.873
What in the world?

17:55.175 --> 17:57.310
[***]

17:58.411 --> 17:59.646
Julius!

17:59.679 --> 18:00.814
Huh?

18:00.847 --> 18:03.149
What in the world
happened in here?

18:03.183 --> 18:04.784
Huh?

18:04.818 --> 18:06.419
I cannot believe...

18:06.453 --> 18:08.722
What is this?
I don't know.

18:08.755 --> 18:11.691
What do you mean you don't know?
It looks like a whirlwind.

18:11.725 --> 18:14.527
Hey, what are you going
to make for dinner?

18:14.561 --> 18:15.662
Huh?

18:15.695 --> 18:17.630
[MAN READS ON-SCREEN TEXT]

18:21.301 --> 18:23.603
Have you lost
your monkey-ass mind?

18:23.636 --> 18:25.171
Dinner?

18:25.205 --> 18:27.374
Do I look like Florence
from<i>The Jeffersons?</i>

18:27.407 --> 18:29.275
Get over here
and pick this crap up

18:29.309 --> 18:31.378
before I smack
the shine off your head.

18:31.411 --> 18:34.214
<i>Today marks the end of</i>
<i>the strike by local truckers,</i>

18:34.247 --> 18:35.849
<i>which began</i>
<i>after one of the drivers</i>

18:35.882 --> 18:37.317
<i>was injured in an explosion</i>

18:37.350 --> 18:39.319
<i>caused by what</i>
<i>the drivers termed</i>

18:39.352 --> 18:40.653
<i>"lack of adequate signage."</i>

18:40.687 --> 18:43.189
<i>An agreement was signed</i>
<i>last night,</i>

18:43.223 --> 18:44.924
<i>and truckers will be back...</i>
Yes!

18:44.958 --> 18:46.292
<i>...on the road tomorrow.</i>

18:46.326 --> 18:48.728
[EXCLAIMS, LAUGHS]

18:48.762 --> 18:50.263
Good morning.

18:50.296 --> 18:51.698
TONYA:
Good morning, Daddy.

18:51.731 --> 18:54.668
Ma, these pancakes
are good.

18:54.701 --> 18:57.737
Yeah, Dad, how come you can't
make pancakes like this?

18:57.771 --> 18:59.339
I don't know.

18:59.372 --> 19:01.841
I just don't have that
touch like your mother.

19:01.875 --> 19:03.610
[***]

19:03.643 --> 19:06.780
Chris, who was that little boy
you were hanging with yesterday?

19:06.813 --> 19:08.214
Who, Fat Mike?

19:08.248 --> 19:10.450
Fool, now you know
you are not supposed

19:10.483 --> 19:11.818
to be calling
somebody fat.

19:11.851 --> 19:13.219
That's his name.

19:13.253 --> 19:14.587
What kind of name
is Fat Mike?

19:14.621 --> 19:16.289
That's just what
they call him.

19:16.322 --> 19:18.224
Well, you just be
careful out there.

19:18.258 --> 19:20.427
And don't let that boy
ride your bike.

19:20.460 --> 19:21.995
That's how your last one
got stolen.

19:22.028 --> 19:24.531
NARRATOR:
<i>As much as my mother</i>
<i>complained</i>

19:24.564 --> 19:27.467
<i>about housework, she hated</i>
<i>to have somebody else do it.</i>

19:27.500 --> 19:30.370
<i>And after my father</i>
<i>got his job back,</i>

19:30.403 --> 19:34.240
<i>she got to do one of the things</i>
<i>she does best...</i>

19:34.274 --> 19:36.242
File your own damn papers.

19:36.276 --> 19:37.744
I do not need this.

19:37.777 --> 19:39.379
My husband has two jobs.

19:39.412 --> 19:41.281
NARRATOR:
<i>With my mother back at home</i>

19:41.314 --> 19:42.882
<i>and my father back at work,</i>

19:42.916 --> 19:45.385
<i>everything was back</i>
<i>to normal again.</i>

19:45.418 --> 19:47.487
Yo, little man,
let me hold a dollar.

19:47.520 --> 19:49.789
I know Fat Mike.
Who?

19:49.823 --> 19:51.391
Fat Mike.
You know me.

19:51.424 --> 19:53.460
I'm the little dude
from across the street.

19:53.493 --> 19:54.928
What's that supposed
to mean?

19:54.961 --> 19:57.630
We don't live
around here.

19:57.664 --> 19:59.632
Help me!

19:59.666 --> 20:01.267
[SCREAMING]

20:01.301 --> 20:02.869
Hey, man...
get back here!

20:02.902 --> 20:07.540
<i>* Everybody Hates Chris </i>

20:11.711 --> 20:13.680
[***]

20:15.015 --> 20:18.451
<i>* Aw, make it funky now </i>
